[!INFO] ‚≠êHumans are the only host of these.üòî

  • ‚≠êPositive culture is the only confirmatory test of enteric fever.
    • Blood - "early in the disease"; Blood culture is the mainstay of diagnosis of enteric fever. Even so, sensitivity is not 100% (40-80%). Time to positive yield is reduced by centrifugation and culture of the buffy coat because the bacteria live inside the WBCs.
    • Urine and faecies - "first week"Source
    • Bone marrow culture is valuable because it remains positive for upto 5 days after commencement of antibiotic therapy.
    • Of little clinical value because it's positive even with previous infection. Also has low specificity.
    • Checks antibodies to O and H antigens of salmonella. (O antigen - cell wall components, H antigen - the flagellar antigen)
    • However, four fold rise in titre is confirmatory.

#2016GM-OCT/Q10 ‚≠ê

  • Drug resistance is a key issue.
  • Resistance is common to chloramphenicol, amoxicillin, cotrimoxazole. - the older antibiotics used of enteric fever.
    • most strains remain sensitive to Gen 3 cephalosporins and azithyromycin.
  • Some indian studies show increasing resistance to ciprofoloxacin but a recurrence of sensitivity to chloramphenicol , cotrimoxazole and ampicillin.
    • In sri lanka, 2016 guideline suggests ceftriaxone for 10-14 days.
  • Most patients can be managed at home with oral antibiotics. - Harrison's.
  • Response:
    • successful treatment in uncomplicated cases results in clinical improvement in 3-5 days, with fever clearance at 4-6 days.
    • Duration Antibiotics 10 - 14 days (or atleast 5 days after resolution of fever)
    • Relapse can happen 2 to 3 weeks after resolution.
  • Carriers: To be treated with 4 weeks of ciprofloxacin (Harrison's)
  • Single dose IM vaccine with booster in 3 years to be given to food handlers.
    • This is the capsular polysaccharide vaccine.
  • The other vaccine (Ty21a) is live attenuated and given as a capsule.
    • Based on O and H antigens.
